  "texts": [
    "In (3), the first term on the right-hand side represents the empirical risk over the local and proxy samples, and the second term is a numerical constraint, which indicates that having more proxy samples, whose number is denoted as m proxy, is beneficial to the generalization performance.",
    "The last two terms in (4) account for the misleading and ambiguous knowledge in distillation.",
    "From Theorem 2, two key implications can be drawn.",
    "Firstly, when there is severe data heterogeneity, the resulting high distribution divergence d G k ðD k,D test Þ,d G k ðD proxy,D test Þ undermines generalization performance.",
    "When the proxy distribution is closer to the test set than the local data, i.e., d G k ðD k,D test Þ ≥ d G k ðD proxy,D test Þ, federated distillation can improve performance compared to independent training."
